              <tr><td><strong>Comparison page</strong></td><td>Why you and not [competitor]?</td><td>Competitive categories, alternatives searches</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>ROI calculator</strong></td><td>What's the financial return?</td><td>High-ticket B2B, procurement-heavy buyers</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real BOFU examples that moved the number</h2>
        <h3>1. SaaS pricing page rebuild</h3>
        <p>A B2B SaaS company added customer testimonials, an ROI calculator, and an FAQ block directly to their pricing page. Conversion jumped from <strong>4.5% to 8.2%</strong> — an 82% lift — because the objections that had been handled on sales calls were now resolved before the buyer ever raised them.</p>

        <h3>2. Industry-specific case study library</h3>
        <p>A marketing agency built dedicated case studies for dentists, law firms, and HVAC contractors. When sales reps attached the matching case study to a proposal, deal velocity improved <strong>22%</strong> because prospects saw a business exactly like theirs succeed.</p>

        <h3>3. Comparison page cluster</h3>
        <p>An email tool published side-by-side pages for [ourtool] vs. [competitor A], [competitor B], and [competitor C]. Combined, the cluster drove 18% of all paid signups within six months — every visitor was already searching for the direct alternative to a named product.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">BOFU vs. MOFU — which content to publish next</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Bottom of funnel</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Buyer has narrowed to 2-3 named vendors</li>
              <li>Content: pricing, demos, comparisons, case studies</li>
              <li>Success metric: demo-to-close, trial-to-paid</li>
              <li>10-20% of content volume, majority of pipeline</li>
              <li>CTA: book demo, start trial, request quote</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4><a href="/glossary/middle-of-funnel/">Middle of funnel</a></h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Buyer is comparing approaches, not vendors</li>
              <li>Content: how-to guides, buyer's guides, category primers</li>
              <li>Success metric: email captures, content downloads</li>
              <li>30-40% of content volume, feeds BOFU</li>
              <li>CTA: download guide, subscribe, join webinar</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>Most teams need more BOFU, not more MOFU. If you can't map every existing MOFU asset to a BOFU next step, you have a leaky funnel.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 BOFU best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Keep pricing on the pricing page.</strong> "Contact us for pricing" costs you 30-50% of qualified visitors who won't hand over their email for a number.</li>
          <li><strong>Match case studies to industry.</strong> A HVAC prospect wants a HVAC case study, not a generic testimonial.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish comparison pages for every named competitor.</strong> If you don't own [yourbrand] vs. [competitor], the competitor does.</li>
          <li><strong>Include specific numbers.</strong> "Increased revenue by 22% in 6 months" outperforms "grew fast" every time.</li>
          <li><strong>Cut demo request forms to 4 fields max.</strong> Name, work email, company, use case. Everything else is asked on the call.</li>
          <li><strong>Instrument every BOFU page.</strong> Conversion rate, source, bounce, form abandonment. If you don't measure it, you can't optimize it.</li>
          <li><strong>Refresh case studies every 6 months.</strong> Stale customer stories with 2022 numbers signal a stalled business.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — over-producing awareness content</div>
          <p>Content teams love writing new blog posts. But if only 5% of content is BOFU, the funnel leaks — you generate traffic without pipeline. Audit your content library by stage. If awareness pieces outnumber decision pieces 10:1, rebalance before publishing anything new.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common BOFU mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Hiding pricing behind a form.</strong> Modern B2B buyers self-research; you filter out the strongest fits.</li>
          <li><strong>Generic case studies.</strong> "Great tool, highly recommend" persuades no one. Named customers with specific numbers persuade everyone.</li>
          <li><strong>No competitor comparisons.</strong> The alternatives search happens with or without you. Ceding the SERP is a choice.</li>
          <li><strong>Demo forms with 12 fields.</strong> Every field drops conversion. Ask what you need to route, nothing more.</li>
          <li><strong>Not tying BOFU pages to pipeline.</strong> If you can't attribute closed-won revenue back to specific BOFU assets, you can't defend the content budget.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps with BOFU</h2>
        <p>theStacc audits your full funnel — awareness, consideration, decision — and identifies the BOFU gaps costing you deals. We map your existing content to funnel stages, surface missing decision-stage assets (pricing objections, competitor comparisons, industry case studies), and prioritize the fixes by expected pipeline impact. Every recommendation is tied to a real revenue number, not a vanity metric.</p>

